5000|$|According to the TV program, the {{demonstration}} of imaging an object in a complete darkness was fabricated. The demonstration was performed by comparing the SMPD and the existing CMOS sensors (camera). Their images were compared as the light was dimmed down to a darkness. During {{the demonstration}}, only the SMPD was able to show the image in darkness, while the CMOS sensors could not. The demonstration looked successful; however, later {{it turned out that}} the testing condition was not identical to both cases. Here is the explanation. An object emits both visible lights and infra-red waves. Under darkness, an object emits only infra-red waves. Typical CMOS sensors can detect both visible lights and infra-red waves. However, when they detect both visible and infra-red waves, the images become less identical to what humans see with their eyes. Thus, typically the CMOS sensors has a filter that block infra-red (IR) waves. Thus, the CMOS sensors could not detect anything in the darkness during the demonstration. On the other hand, the SMPD sensor did not have an <b>IR</b> <b>filter,</b> and thus was able to 'see' the images in the darkness. When the TV program put an <b>IR</b> <b>filter</b> in front of the SMPD sensor, the SMPD sensor image disappeared. [...] Thus, the demonstration in the darkness showed the outcome of the existence of an <b>IR</b> <b>filter,</b> instead of the true performance of the SMPD sensor. The performance comparison under the identical environment was never demonstrated since then. This experiment is a main evidence to support the technical fraud by the SMPD technology.|$|E
